{"title_page": "1968 Greek constitutional referendum", "text_new": "{{Politics of Greece}}\n\nA '''constitutional referendum''' was held in [[Greece]] on 15 November 1968.<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen]] & Philip St\u00f6ver (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p830 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> Voters were asked whether they wished to ratify a [[Greek Constitution of 1968|new constitution]] prepared by the [[Greek military junta of 1967-1974|dictatorial regime]]. It was approved by 92.1% of voters, with a voter turnout of 77.7%.<ref>Nohlen & St\u00f6ver, p838</ref>\n\n==Background==\nA military junta, presided over by Colonel [[Georgios Papadopoulos]], had ruled Greece since a group of middle-ranking officers [[Greek military junta of 1967\u20131974|staged a coup on 21 April 1967]]. [[Constantine II of Greece|King Constantine II]] reluctantly endorsed the coup, but started preparing for a [[counter-coup]] by elements of the armed forces loyal to him. The counter-coup, launched on 13 December 1967, failed, and the King and the royal family fled to [[Italy]]. In the aftermath of the royal coup attempt, the King was replaced by a [[regent]], General [[Georgios Zoitakis]], and Papadopoulos assumed the post of [[Prime Minister of Greece|Prime Minister]].\n\nOn 16 December, Papadopoulos announced that the new constitution, which had been prepared by a committee of legal experts under [[Charilaos Mitrelias]], President of the [[Council of State (Greece)|Council of State]], was to be formally presented to the people on 16 March 1968, and subsequently confirmed by a plebiscite in summer. The original draft of the Mitrelias Committee, however, was deemed too liberal, and was heavily amended in the following months. In its final form, as presented on 11 July 1968, it retained the [[Greek monarchy|monarchy]], but granted the armed forces autonomy from governmental and parliamentary control and entrusted them with the role of guardians of the ''status quo'', it imposed restrictions on political parties and established a constitutional watchdog, the Constitutional Court, with wide-ranging powers, to regulate the country's political life.\n\nThe referendum itself was proclaimed for 29 September, and was regarded by the regime as a public vote of support on its policies. Participation was made obligatory and abstention punishable by imprisonment. The regime employed extensive propaganda in favour of a \"yes\" vote, while any opposition was silenced. The referendum's results were thus predictably in favour of the new constitution. The vote, despite obligatory participation, was still marked by a high abstention, which reached over 22%.\n\n==Results==\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:right\n!Choice\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|align=left|For||4,713,421||92.1\n|-\n|align=left|Against||403,829||7.9\n|-\n|align=left|Invalid/blank votes||16,656||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left|'''Total'''||'''5,133,906'''||'''100'''\n|-\n|align=left|Registered voters/turnout||6,606,111||77.7\n|-\n|align=left colspan=3|Source: Nohlen & St\u00f6ver\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Greek military junta of 1967\u201374}}\n{{Greek elections}}\n\n[[Category:1968 referendums]]\n[[Category:Greek junta]]\n[[Category:Referendums in Greece|Constitutional]]\n[[Category:1968 in Greece]]\n[[Category:1960s in Greek politics]]\n[[Category:Constitutional referendums]]\n[[Category:November 1968 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Politics of Greece}}\n\nA '''constitutional referendum''' was held in [[Greece]] on 15 November 1968.<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen]] & Philip St\u00f6ver (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p830 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> Voters were asked whether they wished to ratify a [[Greek Constitution of 1968|new constitution]] prepared by the [[Greek military junta of 1967-1974|dictatorial regime]]. It was approved by 92.1% of voters, with a voter turnout of 77.7%.<ref>Nohlen & St\u00f6ver, p838</ref>\n\n==Background==\nA military junta, presided over by Colonel [[Georgios Papadopoulos]], had ruled Greece since a group of middle-ranking officers [[Greek military junta of 1967\u20131974|staged a coup on 21 April 1967]]. [[Constantine II of Greece|King Constantine II]] reluctantly endorsed the coup, but started preparing for a [[counter-coup]] by elements of the armed forces loyal to him. The counter-coup, launched on 13 December 1967, failed, and the King and the royal family fled to [[Italy]]. In the aftermath of the royal coup attempt, the King was replaced by a [[regent]], General [[Georgios Zoitakis]], and Papadopoulos assumed the post of [[Prime Minister of Greece|Prime Minister]].\n\nOn 16 December, Papadopoulos announced that the new constitution, which had been prepared by a committee of legal experts under [[Charilaos Mitrelias]], President of the [[Council of State (Greece)|Council of State]], was to be formally presented to the people on 16 March 1968, and subsequently confirmed by a plebiscite in summer. The original draft of the Mitrelias Committee, however, was deemed too liberal, and was heavily amended in the following months. In its final form, as presented on 11 July 1968, it retained the [[Greek monarchy|monarchy]], but granted the armed forces autonomy from governmental and parliamentary control and entrusted them with the role of guardians of the ''status quo'', it imposed restrictions on political parties and established a constitutional watchdog, the Constitutional Court, with wide-ranging powers, to regulate the country's political life.\n\nThe referendum itself was proclaimed for 29 September, and was regarded by the regime as a public vote of support on its policies. Participation was made obligatory and abstention punishable by imprisonment. The regime employed extensive propaganda in favour of a \"yes\" vote, while any opposition was silenced. The referendum's results were thus predictably in favour of the new constitution. The vote, despite obligatory participation, was still marked by a high abstention, which reached over 22%.\n\n==Results==\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:right\n!Choice\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|align=left|For||4,713,421||92.1\n|-\n|align=left|Against||403,829||7.9\n|-\n|align=left|Invalid/blank votes||16,656||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left|'''Total'''||'''5,133,906'''||'''100'''\n|-\n|align=left|Registered voters/turnout||6,606,111||77.7\n|-\n|align=left colspan=3|Source: Nohlen & St\u00f6ver\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Greek military junta of 1967\u201374}}\n{{Greek elections}}\n\n[[Category:1968 referendums]]\n[[Category:Greek military junta of 1967\u20131974]]\n[[Category:Referendums in Greece|Constitutional]]\n[[Category:1968 in Greece]]\n[[Category:1960s in Greek politics]]\n[[Category:Constitutional referendums]]\n[[Category:November 1968 events]]\n", "name_user": "Ceyockey", "label": "safe", "comment": "updating category (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1968_Greek_constitutional_referendum"}
{"title_page": "Ibn al-Tilmidh", "text_new": "{{short description|Syriac Christian physician, pharmacist, poet, musician and calligrapher}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Ibn al-Tilm\u012bdh <br> \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0645\u06cc\u0630\n| birth_name = Habbat-allah Ibn Sad <br> \u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0647\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0635\u0627\u0639\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0647\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0625\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u063a\u062f\u0627\u062f\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0635\u0631\u0627\u0646\u0649\n| birth_date = 1074\n| birth_place = [[Baghdad]], [[Abbasid Caliphate]], now [[Iraq]]\n| death_date = 11 April 1165 (aged 92)\n| death_place = [[Baghdad]], [[Abbasid Caliphate]], now [[Iraq]]\n| occupation = [[Physician]], [[Pharmacology|Pharmacist]], [[Poet]], [[musician]], [[Calligrapher]], <br>As [[physician]] in [[Al-'Adudi Hospital]], [[Baghdad]], now [[Iraq]], <br> Personal physician of Caliph [[Al-Mustadi]]\n| notableworks = Marginal commentary on [[Avicenna]]'s [[The Canon of Medicine]], <br> Al-Aqr\u0101b\u0101dh\u012bn al-Kabir, <br> Maq\u0101lah f\u012b al-fa\u1e63d\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n'''Am\u012bn al-Dawla Abu'l-\u1e24asan Hibat All\u0101h ibn \u1e62a\u02bf\u012bd ibn al-Tilm\u012bdh''' ({{lang-ar|\u0647\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0635\u0627\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0630}}; 1074 \u2013 11 April 1165) was a [[Syriac people|Syriac]] Christian physician, [[pharmacist]], poet, musician and [[calligrapher]].  He was born in then iranian city [[Baghdad]] and lived in [[Isfahan]] and [[Baghdad]] during the reign of Malikshah I and Mahmud I Seljuk in [[Isfahan]].\n\n\nIbn al-Tilmidh worked at the [[\u02bbA\u1e0dud\u012b hospital]] in [[Baghdad]] where he eventually became its chief physician as well as court physician to the caliph [[Al-Mustadi]], and in charge of licensing physicians in Baghdad.<ref name=\"chipman\">{{cite book|last=Chipman|first=Leigh|title=The world of pharmacy and pharmacists in Maml\u016bk Cairo|year=2010|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=90-04-17606-3|pages=31\u201332}}</ref> He mastered the [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[Syriac language|Syriac]] languages.\n\nHe compiled several medical works, the most influential being ''Al-Aqr\u0101b\u0101dh\u012bn al-Kabir'', a pharmacopeia which became the standard pharmacological work in the hospitals of the Islamic civilization, superseding an earlier work by [[Sabur ibn Sahl]].<ref name=\"chipman\" />\n\n==Works==\n* ''Marginal commentary on [[Ibn Sina]]'s [[The Canon of Medicine|\"Canon\"]]''\n* ''Al-Aqr\u0101b\u0101dh\u012bn al-Kabir''\n* ''Maq\u0101lah f\u012b al-fa\u1e63d''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Kahl|first=Oliver|title=The dispensatory of Ibn at-Tilm\u012bd\u0332 : Arabic text, English translation, study and glossaries|year=2007|publisher=Brill|isbn=978-90-04-15620-3}}\n\n{{Islamic medicine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ibn al-Tilmidh}}\n[[Category:1073 births]]\n[[Category:1165 deaths]]\n[[Category:Physicians of medieval Islam]]\n[[Category:Pharmacologists of medieval Islam]]\n[[Category:12th-century physicians]]\n[[Category:Medieval Assyrian physicians]]\n[[Category:Medieval Iraqi physicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Calligraphers]]\n[[Category:12th-century Arabic poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Syriac Christian physician, pharmacist, poet, musician and calligrapher}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Ibn al-Tilm\u012bdh <br> \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0645\u06cc\u0630\n| birth_name = Habbat-allah Ibn Sad <br> \u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0647\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0635\u0627\u0639\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0647\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0625\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u063a\u062f\u0627\u062f\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0635\u0631\u0627\u0646\u0649\n| birth_date = 1074\n| birth_place = [[Baghdad]], [[Abbasid Caliphate]], now [[Iraq]]\n| death_date = 11 April 1165 (aged 92)\n| death_place = [[Baghdad]], [[Abbasid Caliphate]], now [[Iraq]]\n| occupation = [[Physician]], [[Pharmacology|Pharmacist]], [[Poet]], [[musician]], [[Calligrapher]], <br>As [[physician]] in [[Al-'Adudi Hospital]], [[Baghdad]], now [[Iraq]], <br> Personal physician of Caliph [[Al-Mustadi]]\n| notableworks = Marginal commentary on [[Avicenna]]'s [[The Canon of Medicine]], <br> Al-Aqr\u0101b\u0101dh\u012bn al-Kabir, <br> Maq\u0101lah f\u012b al-fa\u1e63d\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n'''Am\u012bn al-Dawla Abu'l-\u1e24asan Hibat All\u0101h ibn \u1e62a\u02bf\u012bd ibn al-Tilm\u012bdh''' ({{lang-ar|\u0647\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0635\u0627\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0630}}; 1074 \u2013 11 April 1165) was a [[Syriac people|Syriac]] Christian physician, [[pharmacist]], poet, musician and [[calligrapher]] of the medieval [[Islamic Golden Age|Islamic civilization]].\n\nIbn al-Tilmidh worked at the [[\u02bbA\u1e0dud\u012b hospital]] in [[Baghdad]] where he eventually became its chief physician as well as court physician to the caliph [[Al-Mustadi]], and in charge of licensing physicians in Baghdad.<ref name=\"chipman\">{{cite book|last=Chipman|first=Leigh|title=The world of pharmacy and pharmacists in Maml\u016bk Cairo|year=2010|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=90-04-17606-3|pages=31\u201332}}</ref> He mastered the [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[Syriac language|Syriac]] languages.\n\nHe compiled several medical works, the most influential being ''Al-Aqr\u0101b\u0101dh\u012bn al-Kabir'', a pharmacopeia which became the standard pharmacological work in the hospitals of the Islamic civilization, superseding an earlier work by [[Sabur ibn Sahl]].<ref name=\"chipman\" />\n\n==Works==\n* ''Marginal commentary on [[Ibn Sina]]'s [[The Canon of Medicine|\"Canon\"]]''\n* ''Al-Aqr\u0101b\u0101dh\u012bn al-Kabir''\n* ''Maq\u0101lah f\u012b al-fa\u1e63d''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Kahl|first=Oliver|title=The dispensatory of Ibn at-Tilm\u012bd\u0332 : Arabic text, English translation, study and glossaries|year=2007|publisher=Brill|isbn=978-90-04-15620-3}}\n\n{{Islamic medicine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ibn al-Tilmidh}}\n[[Category:1073 births]]\n[[Category:1165 deaths]]\n[[Category:Physicians of medieval Islam]]\n[[Category:Pharmacologists of medieval Islam]]\n[[Category:12th-century physicians]]\n[[Category:Medieval Assyrian physicians]]\n[[Category:Medieval Iraqi physicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Calligraphers]]\n[[Category:12th-century Arabic poets]]\n", "name_user": "Firooz Peyravi", "label": "safe", "comment": "some notes about places where he lived.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ibn_al-Tilmidh"}
{"title_page": "Alan Khugaev", "text_new": "{{short description|Russian wrestler}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Alan Khugaev<br>\u0410\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0425\u0443\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0432\n| image          = London 2012 Alan Khugaev.jpg\n| image_size     = 200px\n| caption        = Khugaev at the 2012 Olympics.\n| birth_date     = {{birth-date and age|27 April 1989}}\n| birth_place    = [[Vladikavkaz]], [[Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| headercolor    = lightsteelblue\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport| Men's [[Greco-Roman Wrestling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| {{RUS}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]] | [[Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 84 kg|84&nbsp;kg]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Summer Universiade]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2013 Summer Universiade|2013 Kazan]]|84 kg}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FILA Wrestling European Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2011 European Wrestling Championships|2011 Dortmund]]|84 kg}}\n}}\n\n'''Alan Anatolyevich Khugaev''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0425\u0443\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0432}}, {{lang-os|\u0425\u0443\u044b\u0433\u0430\u0442\u044b \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0439\u044b \u0444\u044b\u0440\u0442 \u0410\u043b\u0430\u043d}});born 27 April 1989 in [[Vladikavkaz]]) is a Russian [[Wrestling|wrestler]] of [[Ossetians|Ossetian]] origin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london2012.com/athlete/khugaev-alan-1022832/|title=Alan Khugaev|publisher=London2012.com|accessdate=August 6, 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130103191740/http://www.london2012.com/athlete/khugaev-alan-1022832/|archive-date=January 3, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He won the gold medal at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in the Greco-Roman men's 84&nbsp;kg event.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/london-olympics-2012/news/Russias-Alan-Khugaev-wins-84kg-greco-roman-gold/articleshow/15381414.cms|title=Russia's Alan Khugaev wins 84kg greco-roman gold|accessdate=August 8, 2012|work=The Times Of India}}</ref>  After retiring from competing, Khugaev was appointed the U23 Greco-Roman coach for the Russian national team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestrus.ru/news/fsbrnews/Novosti_federacii/alan_hugaev_naznachen_starshim_trenerom_sbornoj_rossii_po_greko_rimskoj_bor_be_otvechajushhim_za_vozrast_do_23_let|title=\u0410\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0425\u0443\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0448\u0438\u043c \u0442\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u043e\u043c \u0441\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u043e \u0433\u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e-\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0431\u0435, \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0447\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u043c \u0437\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442 \u0434\u043e 23 \u043b\u0435\u0442 \u2014 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0431\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=www.wrestrus.ru|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Greco-Roman wrestling middleweight}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khugaev, Alan}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic wrestlers of Russia]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Russia]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in wrestling]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Vladikavkaz]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Russian male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Universiade medalists in wrestling]]\n[[Category:Universiade gold medalists for Russia]]\n\n\n{{Russia-sport-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Russian wrestler}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Alan Khugayev<br>\u0410\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0425\u0443\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0432\n| image          = London 2012 Alan Khugaev.jpg\n| image_size     = 200px\n| caption        = Khugayev at the 2012 Olympics.\n| birth_date     = {{birth-date and age|27 April 1989}}\n| birth_place    = [[Vladikavkaz]], [[Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| headercolor    = lightsteelblue\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport| Men's [[Greco-Roman Wrestling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| {{RUS}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]] | [[Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 84 kg|84&nbsp;kg]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Summer Universiade]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2013 Summer Universiade|2013 Kazan]]|84 kg}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FILA Wrestling European Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2011 European Wrestling Championships|2011 Dortmund]]|84 kg}}\n}}\n\n'''Alan Anatolyevich Khugayev''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0425\u0443\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0432}}, {{lang-os|\u0425\u0443\u044b\u0433\u0430\u0442\u044b \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0439\u044b \u0444\u044b\u0440\u0442 \u0410\u043b\u0430\u043d}});born 27 April 1989 in [[Vladikavkaz]]) is a Russian [[Wrestling|wrestler]] of [[Ossetians|Ossetian]] origin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london2012.com/athlete/khugaev-alan-1022832/|title=Alan Khugayev|publisher=London2012.com|accessdate=August 6, 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130103191740/http://www.london2012.com/athlete/khugaev-alan-1022832/|archive-date=January 3, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He won the gold medal at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in the Greco-Roman men's 84&nbsp;kg event.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/london-olympics-2012/news/Russias-Alan-Khugaev-wins-84kg-greco-roman-gold/articleshow/15381414.cms|title=Russia's Alan Khugaev wins 84kg greco-roman gold|accessdate=August 8, 2012|work=The Times Of India}}</ref>  After retiring from competing, Khugaev was appointed the U23 Greco-Roman coach for the Russian national team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestrus.ru/news/fsbrnews/Novosti_federacii/alan_hugaev_naznachen_starshim_trenerom_sbornoj_rossii_po_greko_rimskoj_bor_be_otvechajushhim_za_vozrast_do_23_let|title=\u0410\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0425\u0443\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0448\u0438\u043c \u0442\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u043e\u043c \u0441\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u043e \u0433\u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e-\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0431\u0435, \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0447\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u043c \u0437\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442 \u0434\u043e 23 \u043b\u0435\u0442 \u2014 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0431\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=www.wrestrus.ru|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Greco-Roman wrestling middleweight}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khugayev, Alan}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic wrestlers of Russia]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Russia]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in wrestling]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Vladikavkaz]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Russian male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Universiade medalists in wrestling]]\n[[Category:Universiade gold medalists for Russia]]\n\n\n{{Russia-sport-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Mohsen1248", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/