p=Unnamed\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] foundered in the [[North Sea]] {{convert|20|nmi|km}} off the coast of Aberdeenshire. Her three crew took to a boat; they were rescued by the [[tugboat|tug]] ''Britannia'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=AJ081062>{{Cite news |title=(letter) |author=Amor \u00c6quitatus |newspaper=Aberdeen Journal |location=Abredeen |date=8 October 1862 |issue=5987 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==7 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=7 October 1862|sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''David and John'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore at [[Gosforth]], [[Northumberland]]. She was on a voyage from [[Montrose, Forfarshire]] to [[Seaham]], [[County Durham]].<ref name=S091062/> She was refloated the next day and towed in to [[Berwick upon Tweed]], Northumberland.<ref name=S101062>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=10 October 1862 |issue=11907 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Dunkirk''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[CSS Alabama's New England Expeditionary Raid|CSS ''Alabama''{{'}}s New England Expeditionary Raid]]: During a voyage from [[New York City|New York]] to [[Lisbon]], Portugal, with a cargo of [[flour]] and [[Portuguese language]] [[bible]]s, the 293-ton [[brig]] was captured and burned in the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] southeast of [[Nova Scotia]], [[British North America]] by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Alabama|CSS ''Alabama'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America}}).<ref name=macslogalabama/><ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862/><ref name=gainesp32/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Elizabeth''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[collier (ship type)|collier]], a [[brig]], was run down and sunk in the [[North Sea]] off the ''[[Sunk Lightship]]'' ([[File:Trinity House Ensign (pre-1937).svg|22px]] [[Trinity House]]) by a [[steamship]] with the loss of five of her crew.<ref name=Times131062>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=13 October 1862 |page_number=10 |issue=24375 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Forrester''<!--{{PS|Forrester|1848|2}}?-->, and<br>{{PS|Tynemouth|1862|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] ''Forrester'' was run into by the [[paddle steamer]] ''Tynemouth'' and sank in the [[River Tyne]] with the loss of six lives. She was on a voyage from [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]] to [[South Shields]], [[County Durham]]. ''Tynemouth'' was on a voyage from South Shields to Newcastle upon Tyne. She was severely damaged and was beached.<ref name=Times091062>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Fearful Steamboat Collision |date=9 October 1862 |page_number=9 |issue=24372 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=CM091062>{{Cite news |title=Terrible Steamboat Disaster on the Tyne |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=9 October 1862 |issue=22857 }}</ref><ref name=NC101062>{{Cite news |title=Collision on the River Tyne |newspaper=Newcastle Courant |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=10 October 1862 |issue=9798 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Kate McLea'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was sighted off \"Bic Island\", [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]] whilst on a voyage from [[Montreal]], Province of Canada to [[Exeter]], [[Devon]]. No further trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=DC251262>{{Cite news |title=Dundee Shipping |newspaper=Dundee Courier |location=Dundee |date=25 December 1862 |issue=2925 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Libra''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] {{convert|200|nmi|km}} from [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt Eyalet|Egypt]]. Her crew survived. She was on a voyage from Alexandria to [[Falmouth, Cornwall]].<ref name=Times091062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered off the north coast of [[Norfolk]].<ref name=S091062>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=9 October 1862 |issue=11906 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Maryland''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was lost at [[Cape Mendocino]], [[California]], [[Confederate States of America]].<ref name=gainesp28>Gaines, p. 28.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Primera de Torrevieja''\n|flag={{flag|Spain|civil-1785}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Holyhead]], [[Anglesey]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]], United Kingdom to the [[rio de la Plata|River Plate]]. She was refloated with assistance from the [[tugboat|tug]] ''Storm King'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=Times091062a>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=9 October 1862 |page_number=11 |issue=24372 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=LM081062>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=8 October 1862 |issue=4574 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Wave Crest''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War, [[CSS Alabama's New England Expeditionary Raid|CSS ''Alabama''{{'}}s New England Expeditionary Raid]]: During a voyage to [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]], United Kingdom with a cargo of [[grain]], the 409-ton [[barque]] was captured, used for target practice, and burned in the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] southeast of Nova Scotia by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Alabama|CSS ''Alabama'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America}}).<ref name=macslogalabama/><ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862/><ref name=gainesp32/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==8 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=8 October 1862 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Blanche''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: Pursued by the [[screw steamer]] {{USS|Montgomery|1858|6}} ({{navy|United States|1861}}), the sidewheel [[paddle steamer]], a [[Blockade runners of the American Civil War|blockade runner]], ran aground at [[Marianao]], [[Captaincy General of Cuba|Cuba]], and a boat crew from ''Montgomery'' boarded and seized her. Soon afterward, while the boat crew attempted to refloat her, a fire broke out which destroyed her and her cargo.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862/><ref>[https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/nhhc/research/histories/ship-histories/confederate_ships/general-rusk.html Naval History and Heritage Command: Confederate Ships: General Rusk]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WwNHAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA867&lpg=PA867&dq=%22General+Rusk%22+Cuba+1862&source=bl&ots=B3Fcq2Ynz-&sig=hrReE5cyQMHJXmN7IJHLPrtI-4o&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBxdORgtLVAhVq3IMKHbQZDXcQ6AEILzAC#v=onepage&q=%22General%20Rusk%22%20Cuba%201862&f=false Anonymous, ''Official Records of the Union and Confederate Navies in the War of the Rebellion'', Washington, D.C.: Government Printing Office, 1905, pp. 274-275.]</ref><ref>Gaines, p. 33.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Denmark''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The 283-ton sidewheel [[paddle steamer]] struck a [[Snag (ecology)|snag]] and sank in the [[Missouri River]] at [[Atlas Island]] below [[Keokuk, Iowa]].<ref>Gaines, pp. 93, 106.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Francis Elmor'' (or&nbsp;''Francis&nbsp;Elmore'')\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War: Carrying a cargo of [[hay]], the [[schooner]] was captured and burned by [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] forces in the [[Potomac River]]  at [[Popes Creek (Virginia)|Popes Creek]], [[Virginia]], [[Confederate States of America]].<ref name=gainesp180>Gaines, p. 180.</ref> \