m of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]], was captured and burned in the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|40|11|28|N|64|32|15|W}}) by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Alabama|CSS ''Alabama'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America}}).<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862/><ref name=macslogalabama/><ref name=gainesp13>Gaines, p. 13.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Dolphin'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground off [[Skagen]], Denmark. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[Nibe]], Denmark.<ref name=S311062/><ref name=NC071162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Elizabeth Jane''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] capsized in the [[North Sea]] off [[Terschelling]], [[Friesland]], Netherlands. Five of her eight crew were rescued by the [[smack (ship)|smack]] ''Patience'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Elizabeth Jane'' was on a voyage from [[London]] to [[klaip\u0117da|Memel]], [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]].<ref name=Times281062a/> ''Elizabeth Jane'' was discovered by the [[fishing smack]] ''Miranda and Fanny'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and towed in to [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]].<ref name=S041162>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=4 November 1862 |issue=11928 |page=3 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Emeline'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was abandoned in the North Sea {{convert|11|nmi|km}} off [[Heligoland]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from London to [[South Shields]], [[County Durham]].<ref name=S301062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Fadrenes Inmoe'' \n|flag={{flag|Norway|1844}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Kristiansand]]. She was on a voyage from [[Sandefjord]] to [[Leith]], [[Lothian]], United Kingdom.<ref name=S281062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mariner''