orfolk]].<ref name=S091062>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=9 October 1862 |issue=11906 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Maryland''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was lost at [[Cape Mendocino]], [[California]], [[Confederate States of America]].<ref name=gainesp28>Gaines, p. 28.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Primera de Torrevieja''\n|flag={{flag|Spain|civil-1785}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Holyhead]], [[Anglesey]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]], United Kingdom to the [[rio de la Plata|River Plate]]. She was refloated with assistance from the [[tugboat|tug]] ''Storm King'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=Times091062a>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=9 October 1862 |page_number=11 |issue=24372 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=LM081062>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=8 October 1862 |issue=4574 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Wave Crest''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War, [[CSS Alabama's New England Expeditionary Raid|CSS ''Alabama''{{'}}s New England Expeditionary Raid]]: During a voyage to [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]], United Kingdom with a cargo of [[grain]], the 409-ton [[barque]] was captured, used for target practice, and burned in the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] southeast of Nova Scotia by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Alabama|CSS ''Alabama'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America}}).<ref name=macslogalabama/><ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862/><ref name=gainesp32/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==8 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=8 October 1862 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Blanche''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: Pursued by the [[screw steamer]] {{USS|Montgomery|1858|6}} ({{navy|United States|1861}}), the sidewheel [[paddle steamer]], a [[Blockade runners of the American Civil War|blockade runner]], ran aground at [[Marianao]], [[Captaincy General of Cuba|Cuba]], and a boat crew from ''Montgomery'' boarded and seized her. Soon afterward, while the boat crew attempted to refloat her, a fire broke out which destroyed her and her cargo.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862/><ref>[https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/nhhc/research/histories/ship-histories/confederate_ships/general-rusk.html Naval History and Heritage Command: Confederate Ships: General Rusk]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WwNHAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA867&lpg=PA867&dq=%22General+Rusk%22+Cuba+1862&source=bl&ots=B3Fcq2Ynz-&sig=hrReE5cyQMHJXmN7IJHLPrtI-4o&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBxdORgtLVAhVq3IMKHbQZDXcQ6AEILzAC#v=onepage&q=%22General%20Rusk%22%20Cuba%201862&f=false Anonymous, ''Official Records of the Union and Confederate Navies in the War of the Rebellion'', Washington, D.C.: Government Printing Office, 1905, pp. 274-275.]</ref><ref>Gaines, p. 33.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Denmark''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The 283-ton sidewheel [[paddle steamer]] struck a [[Snag (ecology)|snag]] and sank in the [[Missouri River]] at [[Atlas Island]] below [[Keokuk, Iowa]].<ref>Gaines, pp. 93, 106.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Francis Elmor'' (or&nbsp;''Francis&nbsp;Elmore'')\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War: Carrying a cargo of [[hay]], the [[schooner]] was captured and burned by [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] forces in the [[Potomac River]]  at [[Popes Creek (Virginia)|Popes Creek]], [[Virginia]], [[Confederate States of America]].<ref name=gainesp180>Gaines, p. 180.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Galatea'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship departed from [[Dartmouth, Devon]] for [[Dundalk]], [[County Louth]]. No further trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=S021262>{{Cite news |title=Mercatile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=2 December 1862 |issue=11952 |page=2 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pace'' \n|flag=[[File:Austria-Hungary-flag-1869-1914-naval-1786-1869-merchant.svg|22px]] [[Austrian Empire]] \n|desc=The [[barque]] ran aground in the [[River Suir]]. She was on a voyage from [[Sulina]], [[Ottoman Empire]] to [[Waterford]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was refloated but found to be leaky.<ref name=LM091062>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=9 October 1862 |issue=4575 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==9 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=9 October 1862|sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ceres''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The 217-ton sidewheel [[paddle steamer]] exploded at [[St. Joseph Island (Louisiana)|St. Joseph Island]], [[Louisiana]].<ref name=gainesp61>Gaines, p. 61.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Countess'', or<br>''Countess of London''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on [[Anticosti Island]], [[Nova Scotia]], [[British North America]]. She was on a voyage from [[Quebec City]], [[Province of Canada]], British North America to [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]].<ref name=Times251162/> Her crew survived. Some of them took to a boat; they were rescued by the steamship ''Caledonia'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). The rest reached Anticosti Island.<ref name=GH241162>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Glasgow Herald |location=Glasgow |date=24 November 1862 |issue=7136 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Eliza''\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States of America|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: Carrying a cargo of [[sugar]], the [[sloop]] was captured and destroyed at [[Calcasieu, Louisiana]], on or about 9 October.<ref name=gainesp64>Gaines, p. 64.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Familien Store'' \n|flag={{flag|Sweden|1844}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore on the coast of [[Essex]] or [[Suffolk]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was on a voyage from [[Gothenburg]] to [[Algiers]], [[French Algeria|Algeria]]. She was refloated  the next day and taken in to [[Harwich]], Essex.<ref name=S131062>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=13 October 1862 |issue=11909 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lady Clarendon'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Ranka Folah, in the [[Hooghly River]]. She was on a voyage from [[Calcutta]], [[British Raj|India]] to [[Colombo]], [[Ceylon]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=LM171162>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=17 November 1862 |issue=4608 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Parana'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was wrecked in [[Simon's Bay]].<ref name=LM291162>{{Cite news |title=The Cape of Good Hope |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=29 November 1862 |issue=4619 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==10 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=10 October 1862 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Elizabeth'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the [[Kentish Knock (England)|Kentish Knock]]. Her crew were rescued by ''Marco Polo'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}.<ref name=Benham/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==11 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=11 October 1862|sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Argyll''\n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[British Guiana]]\n|desc=The [[brig]] departed from [[New York City|New York]] for [[Barbadoes]]. No furthre trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=Times150163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Shipping Intelligence |date=15 January 1863 |page_number=10 |issue=24456 |column=D }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Gem'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] struck a rock off [[Burravoe]] [[Shetland Islands]] and was beached. She was later refloated.<ref name=S301062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Gezina'' \n|flag=Flag unknown\n|desc=The ship was sighted off [[Skagen]], Denmark whilst on a voyage from [[Riga]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]] to [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. No further trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=S080163>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=8 January 1863 |issue=11984 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Manchester''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[CSS Alabama's New England Expeditionary Raid|CSS ''Alabama''{{'}}s New England Expeditionary Raid]]: The 1,062-ton [[full-rigged ship]], carrying a cargo of [[grain]] from [[New York City|New York]] to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]], United Kingdom, was captured and burned in the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] southeast of [[Nova Scotia]], [[British North America]] ({{coord|44|08|55|N|55|26|00|W}}) by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Alabama|CSS ''Alabama'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America}}).<ref name=macslogalabama/><ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862/><ref name=gainesp32/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==12 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=12 October 1862|sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Foreman'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Newburgh, Fife]]. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=S221062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{PS|Hamburg|1849|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[paddle steamer]] was driven ashore at [[Scotstoun Head]], [[Aberdeenshire]]. All on board survived. She was on a voyage from [[Kirkwall]], [[Orkney Islands]] to [[Aberdeen]]. She broke in two on 15 October.<ref name=Times171062/><ref name=LM201062>{{Cite news |title=Loss of Two Steamers |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=20 October 1862 |issue=4584 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Hannah''\n|flag={{army|CSA}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: The armed [[schooner]] ran aground {{convert|7|mi|km}} north of [[Corpus Christi, Texas]]. Her crew burned her soon thereafter when a boat party from a [[United States Navy]] warship that anchored {{convert|400|yd|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} away made preparations to approach and board ''Hannah''.<ref>[https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/nhhc/research/histories/ship-histories/confederate_ships/hannah.html Naval History and Heritage Command: Confederate Ships: Hannah]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Myrtle'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship caught fire in the [[English Channel]] and was beached at Smallmouth, [[Dorset]]. She was on a voyage from [[Antwerp]], Belgium to [[Weymouth, Dorset]]. She was refloated the next day and towed in to Weymouth.<ref name=S161062>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=16 October 1862 |issue=11913 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==13 October==\n:''For the wreck of ''Geneva'' on this date, see the entry for [[List of shipwrecks in September 1862#24 September|24 September 1862]]''\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=13 October 1862 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ann'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] was driven ashore in [[Carnarvon Bay]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Pwllheli]], [[Caernarfonshire]] to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]].<ref name=S161062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|