|flag=[[File:Flagge Gro\u00dfherzogt\u00fcmer Mecklenburg.svg|22px]] [[Grand Duchy of Mecklenburg-Schwerin]] \n|desc=The ship [foundered before 28 October. She was on a voyage from [[Wolgast]] to [[Leith]], [[Lothian]], United Kingdom.<ref name=S031162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Frederick'' \n|flag=[[file:Flagge der Hansestadt Rostock.svg|22px]] [[Rostock]] \n|desc=The ship was lost near [[Farsund]], Norway.<ref name=DC231062>{{Cite news |title=Dundee Shipping |newspaper=Dundee Courier |location=Dundee |date=23 October 1862 |issue=2871 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Garland''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the Atlantic Ocean. She was on a voyage from [[Sombrero, Anguilla]] to Queenstown.<ref name=LM011262/> She was driven ashore and severely damaged on the [[Mull of Kintyre]], [[Argyllshire]] on 17 October.<ref name=Times231062a/> She became a wreck on 22 October.<ref name=Times251062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''General Hewitt'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned at sea. She was on a voyage from Liverpool to Shanghai.<ref name=LM031162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''General Taylor''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The 462-ton [[screw steamer]] was stranded at [[Sleeping Bear Point Life Saving Station|Sleeping Bear Point]] on the [[Lake Michigan]] coast of [[Michigan]].<ref name=gainesp81>Gaines, p. 81.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''George Robson''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in the North Sea off [[Sylt]], [[Duchy of Holstein]] before 26 October with loss of life.<ref name=Times041162>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=4 November 1862 |page_number=11 |issue=24394 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Go-a-head'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was lost at \"Curampe\".<ref name=LM151062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Gruber'' \n|flag={{flag|Kingdom of Hanover|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore on the west coast of Denmark. She was on a voyage from [[Papenburg]] to the [[River Tyne]].<ref name=NC311062>{{Cite news |title=Marine Intelligence |newspaper=Newcastle Courant |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=31 October 1862 |issue=9801 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Hudson''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was abandoned in the Atlantic Ocean before 20 October.<ref name=Times251162/><ref name=LM080163>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=8 January 1863 |issue=4663 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jane Morell'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore near [[Domesnes]], Russia.<ref name=LM171062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jasper'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered before 29 October. She was on a voyage from [[Rostock]] to [[Dundee]], [[Forfarshire]].<ref name=S311062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Kate''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Maryport]], [[Cumberland]] before 22 October.<ref name=Times241062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Kate'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] was lost in the [[Yangtze]] before 4 October.<ref name=LM291162a>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=29 November 1862 |issue=4619 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Kate''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] ran aground on the Action Shoal, in the Yangtze and capsized with the loss of five passengers before 5 October. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=Times281162>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=28 November 1862 |page_number=9 |issue=24415 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Keepsake''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at Maryport. She was refloated on 22 October and taken in to Maryport.<ref name=Times241062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Laurel'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Brouwers Reef. She was on a voyage from [[Shanghai]], [[qing dynasty|China]] to London. She was refloated and taken in to [[jakarta|Batavia]], [[Netherlands East Indies]].<ref name=NC020163>{{Cite news |title=Marine Intelligence |newspaper=Newcastle Courant |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=2 January 1863 |issue=9108 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Llagothland'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in the North Sea. She was on a voyage from South Shields to London.<ref name=S011162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mathew'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was wrecked. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=GH251062a>{{Cite news |title=Latest News |newspaper=Glasgow Herald |location=London |date=25 October 1862 |issue=7111 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Marion''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked near \"Larachaque\", [[Nova Scotia]], [[British North America]] before 8 October. She was on a voyage from [[Belfast]], [[County Antrim]] to [[Miramichi, New Brunswick]], British North America.<ref name=Times201062>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=20 October 1862 |page_number=9 |issue=24381 |column=D }}</ref><ref name=BNL181062>{{Cite news |title=Latest News |newspaper=Belfast News-Letter |location=Belfast |date=18 October 1862 |issue=15412 }}</ref><ref name=GH181062>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Glasgow Herald |location=Glasgow |date=18 October 1862 |issue=7105 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary Ann''\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War: The [[schooner]] was captured and burned on the [[Calcasieu River]] in [[Louisiana]] in early October by the [[Steamship|steamer]] {{USS|Kensington|1862|6}} ({{navy|United States|1861}}).<ref name=gainesp70>Gaines, p. 70.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Meannais'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The ship collided with another vessel and sank. She was on a voyage from [[Swansea]], [[Glamorgan]], United Kingdom to [[La Rochelle]], [[Charente-Inf\u00e9rieure]].<ref name=LM031162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Messenger'' \n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[Saint Lucia]]\n|desc=The [[drogher]] was lost at Saint Lucia.<ref name=LM151062>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=15 October 1862 |issue=4580 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Meteor'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in the North Sea before 23 October.<ref name=S011162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Nana''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in the North Sea before 25 October. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[Swinem\u00fcnde]], [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]].<ref name=Times271062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Neva''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[collier (ship type)|collier]], a [[brig]], foundered in the [[North Sea]] before 28 October. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=Times301062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pacific'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship departed from Hamburg in mid-October. Subsequently reported missing.<ref name=NC071162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Prince of Wales|1861|2}}\n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[New South Wales]]\n|desc=The [[steamship]] was wrecked at [[Camden Haven]].<ref name=Times160163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Australia |date=16 January 1863 |page_number=4 |issue=24457 |column=A-D }}</ref><ref name=PoW>{{cite web |url=http://www.theshipslist.com/ships/lines/asnc.shtml |title=Queensland Steam Shipping Co. / Australasian United S.N. Co |publisher=The Ships List |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Santa Maria'' \n|flag=Flag unknown\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on [[L\u00e6s\u00f8]], Denmark.<ref name=LM241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Shepherd''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[collier (ship type)|collier]], a [[brig]], foundered in the North Sea before 28 October. She was on a voyage from [[South Shields]], [[County Durham]] to [[Chatham, Kent]].<ref name=Times301062>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The North Sea. - Shields, Oct. 28 |date=30 October 1862 |page_number=5 |issue=24390 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sofia B'' \n|flag=[[File:Flag of the United States of the Ionian Islands.svg|22px]] [[United States of the Ionian Islands]] \n|desc=The ship was wrecked at [[Sulina]], [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref name=LM211062b/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Surinam''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked in the [[Strait of Belle Isle]] before 15 October. She was on a voyage from the [[River Clyde|Clyde]] to Quebec City.<ref name=Times281062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sydney Jones'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore. She was on a voyage from [[porthmadog|Portmadoc]], [[Caernarfonshire]] to [[Rostock]]. She was refloated and taken in to [[Helsing\u00f8r]], Denmark.<ref name=LM211062b/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Telegraph'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked at Sulina.<ref name=LM211062b/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Token''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was abandoned in the Atlantic Ocean before 26 February. Thirteen crew were rescued by ''Speculant'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Token'' was on a voyage from [[Belize City]], [[British Honduras]] to [[Queenstown, County Cork]].<ref name=Times271062/><ref name=S271062b/><ref name=ES311062>{{Cite news |title=The Late Terrific Gales at Sea |newspaper=Essex Standard |location=Colchester |date=31 October 1862 |issue=1663 |page=1 |volume=32 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Tom Cochrane''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1860}}\n|desc=The 14-ton [[screw steamer]] was stranded at [[Sturgeon Point Light|Sturgeon Point]] on the [[Lake Huron]] coast of Michigan.<ref name=gainesp81/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Whim''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in the North Sea. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Hamburg]] to [[Hartlepool]], County Durham.<ref name=Times011162/><ref name=NC071162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''William Henry''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was run into by the [[full-rigged ship]] ''Reliance'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and was abandoned. Her crew were rescued by ''Reliance''. ''William Henry'' was on a voyage from [[Boston, Massachusetts]], United States to Liverpool.<ref name=Times231062a/><ref name=SI221062/> She had come ashore near [[Blackpool]], Lancashire by 22 October.<ref name=Times241062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Yarmouth'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked near [[Varberg]], Sweden.<ref name=LM171062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* [http://scubagonewild.com/documents/Encyclopedia%20of%20Civil%20War%20Shipwrecks%20-%20(Malestrom).pdf Gaines, W. Craig, ''Encyclopedia of Civil War Shipwrecks'', Louisiana State University Press, 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-8071-3274-6}}.]\n\n{{shipevents|1862}}\n{{1860s shipwrecks}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of shipwrecks by year|1862-10]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in October 1862]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e20 October:Fixing links to disambiguation pages, improving links, other minor cleanup tasks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_shipwrecks_in_October_1862"}
{"title_page": "Gichin Funakoshi", "text_new": "{{short description|Karateka}}\n{{Okinawan name|Funakoshi}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name = Gichin Funakoshi\n| native_name = {{nihongo2|\u8239\u8d8a \u7fa9\u73cd}} \n| native_name_lang = jp\n| residence = \n| other_names = ''Sh\u014dt\u014d'' ([[wikt:\u677e|\u677e]][[wikt:\u6fe4|\u6fe4]])\n| image = [[File:Master Gichin Funakoshi.jpg|thumb|Master Gichin Funakoshi]]\n| image_size = \n| caption = Gichin Funakoshi, ''c.'' 1950\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1868|11|10|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Shuri, Okinawa|Shuri]], [[Ryukyu Kingdom]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1957|04|26|1868|11|10|mf=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Tokyo, Japan]]\n| death_cause = \n| martial_art = [[Sh\u014drei-ry\u016b]], [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b]], and [[Sh\u014dt\u014dkan|Shotokan]] [[Karate]]\n| teacher = [[Ank\u014d Asato]], [[Ank\u014d Itosu]], [[Matsumura S\u014dkon]]\n| rank = 5th dan, 10th ''[[Dan rank|dan]]'' (posthumous)\n| students = [[Hironori \u014ctsuka]], [[Gig\u014d Funakoshi]] (his son), [[Isao Obata]], [[:de:Gima Makoto|Makoto Gima]] [[Shigeru Egami]], [[Teruyuki Okazaki]], [[Tetsuhiko Asai]], [[Masatoshi Nakayama]], [[Yasuhiro Konishi]], [[Hidetaka Nishiyama]], [[Tsutomu Ohshima]], [[Taiji Kase]], [[Mitsusuke Harada]], [[Hirokazu Kanazawa]], [[Won Kuk Lee]], [[Masutatsu Oyama]], [[Tetsuji Murakami]], [[Yutaka Yaguchi]], [[Won Kuk Lee]], [[Song Moo Kwan|Byung Jik Ro]], [[Choi Hong Hi]]\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Gichin Funakoshi'''|\u8239\u8d8a \u7fa9\u73cd|Funakoshi Gichin|November 10, 1868&nbsp;\u2013 April 26, 1957}} is the founder of [[Shotokan]] [[Karate|Karate-Do]], perhaps the most widely known style of karate, and is known as a \"father of modern karate\".<ref>{{cite book | title=Karate Jutsu: The Original Teachings of Master Funakoshi | publisher=Kodansha International Ltd | author=Funakoshi, Gichin | translator=John Teramoto | year=2001 |isbn= 4-7700-2681-1}}</ref> Following the teachings of [[Anko Itosu]] and [[Anko Asato]],<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\">Funakoshi, Gichin (1981). ''Karate-Do: My Way of Life'', Kodansha International Ltd. {{ISBN|0-87011-463-8}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gichinfunakoshi.com/gichin.htm |title=GichinFunakoshi.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005220243/http://www.gichinfunakoshi.com/gichin.htm |archivedate=2012-10-05 }}</ref> he was one of the Okinawan [[karate]] [[Grandmaster (martial arts)|masters]] who introduced karate to the Japanese mainland in 1922. He taught karate at various Japanese universities and became honorary head of the [[Japan Karate Association]] upon its establishment in 1949.\n\n==Early life==\nGichin Funakoshi was born on November 10, 1868,<ref>{{Cite book|author=Gichin Funakoshi |title=Karate-d\u014d, My Way of Life }}</ref> the year of the [[Meiji Restoration]], in [[Shuri, Okinawa]], to a low-rank Ry\u016bky\u016ban [[Pechin]]. He originally had the family name Tominakoshi.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.24fightingchickens.com/2006/01/29/funakoshi-man-vs-myth/ | title = Deconstructing Funakoshi}}</ref> Funakoshi was born [[premature birth|prematurely]]. His father's name was Gisu.<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\"/> After entering primary school he became close friends with the son of [[Ank\u014d Asato]], a karate and [[Jigen-ry\u016b]] master who would soon become his first karate teacher.<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\"/> \n\u2212\t\nFunakoshi's family was stiffly opposed to the Meiji government's abolition of the Japanese [[Chonmage|topknot]], and this meant that he would be ineligible to pursue his goal of attending medical school (where topknots were banned), despite having passed the entrance examination.<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\"/> Being trained in both classical Chinese and Japanese philosophies and teachings, Funakoshi became an assistant teacher in Okinawa. During this time, his relations with the Asato family grew and he began nightly travels to the Asato family residence to receive karate instruction from Ank\u014d Asato.<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\"/>\n\n==Shotokan Karate==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=November 2017}}\nFunakoshi had trained in both of the popular styles of Okinawan [[karate]] of the time: [[Sh\u014drei-ry\u016b]] and [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b]]. Shotokan is named after Funakoshi's pen name, ''Sh\u014dt\u014d'' ([[wikt:\u677e|\u677e]][[wikt:\u6fe4|\u6fe4]]), which means \"waving pines\".  ''Kan'' means training hall or house, thus ''Sh\u014dt\u014dkan'' (\u677e\u6fe4\u9928) referred to the \"house of Sh\u014dt\u014d\". This name was coined by Funakoshi's students when they posted a sign above the entrance of the hall at which Funakoshi taught. In addition to being a karate master, Funakoshi was an avid [[poet]] and [[philosopher]] who would reportedly go for long walks in the forest where he would [[meditation|meditate]] and write his poetry.<ref name=\"threemasters\">John Stevens (1995). \"Three Budo Masters: Kano, Funakoshi, Ueshiba\". Kodansha International {{ISBN|4-7700-1852-5}}</ref>\n\nBy the late 1910s, Funakoshi had many students, of which a few were deemed capable of passing on their master's teachings. Continuing his effort to garner widespread interest in Okinawan karate, Funakoshi ventured to mainland Japan in 1917, and again in 1922.<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\" />\n\nIn 1930, Funakoshi established an association named Dai-Nihon Karate-do Kenkyukai to promote communication and information exchange among people who study karate-d\u014d. In 1936, Dai-Nippon Karate-do Kenkyukai changed its name to Dai-Nippon Karate-do Shoto-kai.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shotokai.jp/english/about/history.html |title=The Official Homepage of Nihon Karate-do Shotokai |access-date=2010-08-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100227032101/http://www.shotokai.jp/english/about/history.html |archive-date=2010-02-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The association is known today as [[Shotokai]], and is the official keeper of Funakoshi's karate heritage.\n\nIn 1936, Funakoshi built the first Sh\u014dt\u014dkan ''[[dojo]]'' (training hall) in Tokyo. While on the Japanese mainland, he changed the [[kanji|written characters]]  of karate to mean \"empty hand\" (\u7a7a\u624b) instead of \"China hand\" (\u5510\u624b) (literally [[Tang dynasty]]) to downplay its connection to [[Chinese boxing]]. Karate had borrowed many aspects from Chinese boxing.  Funakoshi also argued in his autobiography that a philosophical evaluation of the use of \"empty\" seemed to fit as it implied a way which was not tethered to any other physical object.\n\nFunakoshi's re-interpretation of the [[kanji|character]] ''kara'' in karate to mean \"empty\" ([[wikt:\u7a7a|\u7a7a]]) rather than \"Chinese\" ([[wikt:\u5510|\u5510]])  caused some tension with traditionalists back in Okinawa, prompting Funakoshi to remain in [[Tokyo]] indefinitely.{{citation needed|date=May 2010}} In 1949 Funakoshi's students created the [[Japan Karate Association]] (JKA), with Funakoshi as the honorary head of the organization. However, in practise this organization was led by [[Masatoshi Nakayama]]. The JKA began formalizing Funakoshi's teachings. Funakoshi was not supportive of all of the changes that the JKA eventually made to his karate style. He resigned from the JKA in 1956 in order to reduce friction between the JKA and Shotokai.\n\n==Illness and death==\nFunakoshi developed [[osteoarthritis]] in 1948, and died of [[colorectal cancer]] in 1957.\n\n==Legacy==\nFunakoshi published several books on karate including his autobiography, ''Karate-Do: My Way of Life''. His legacy, however, rests in a document containing his philosophies of karate training now referred to as the ''[[niju kun]]'', or \"twenty principles\".  These rules are the premise of training for all Shotokan practitioners and are published in a work titled ''The Twenty Guiding Principles of Karate''.<ref>{{cite book | title=The Twenty Guiding Principles of Karate: The Spiritual Legacy of the Master  | publisher=Kodansha International Ltd | author=Funakoshi, Gichin | translator=John Teramoto| year=1975 |isbn=4-7700-2796-6}}</ref> Within this book, Funakoshi lays out 20 rules by which students of karate are urged to abide in an effort to \"become better human beings\".<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\" /> Funakoshi's Karate-Do Kyohan \"The Master Text\" remains his most detailed publication, containing sections on history, basics, [[kata]], and [[kumite]]. The famous Shotokan Tiger by Hoan<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.funakoshibooks.com/?p=8 | title = Kosugi Hoan Shotokan Tiger}}</ref> adorns the hardback cover.\n\n==Memorial==\n[[File:funakoshi memorial.jpg|thumb|right|Memorial for Funakoshi at Engaku-ji temple in Kamakura, south of Tokyo]]\n\nA memorial to Gichin Funakoshi was erected by the Shotokai at [[Engaku-ji]], a temple in [[Kamakura, Kanagawa|Kamakura]], on December 1, 1968. Designed by Kenji Ogata the monument features calligraphy by Funakoshi and [[S\u014dgen Asahina]] (1891\u20131979), chief priest of the temple which reads ''Karate ni sente nashi'' (There is no first attack in karate), the second of Funakoshi\u2019s Twenty Precepts.  To the right of Funakoshi\u2019s precept is a copy of the poem he wrote on his way to Japan in 1922.\n\nA second stone features an inscription by Nobuhide Ohama and reads:<ref>{{cite book | last = Cook | first = Harry | title = Shotokan Karate: A Precise History | publisher = Cook | year = 2001 | location = England }}</ref>\n\n{{cquote | Funakoshi Gichin Sensei, of karate-do, was born on November 10, 1868 in Shuri Okinawa. From about eleven years old he began to study to-te jutsu under [[Azato Anko]] and [[Itosu Anko]]. He practiced diligently and in 1912 became the president of the Okinawan Shobukai. In May 1922, he relocated to Tokyo and became a professional teacher of karate-do. He devoted his entire life to the development of karate-do. He lived out his eighty-eight years of life and left this world on April 26, 1957. Reinterpreting to-te jutsu, the Sensei promulgated karate-do while not losing its original philosophy. Like bugei (classical martial arts), so too is the pinnacle of karate \u201cmu\u201d (enlightenment): to purify and make one empty through the transformation from \u201cjutsu\u201d to \u201cdo\u201d. Through his famous words \"\u7a7a\u624b\u306b\u5148\u624b\u306a\u3057\" (karate ni sente nashi) meaning ''There is no first attack in Karate'' and \u7a7a\u624b\u306f\u541b\u5b50\u306e\u6b66\u82b8 (karate wa kunshi no bugei) meaning ''Karate is the martial art of intelligent people'', Sensei helped us to better understand the term \u201cjutsu.\u201d In an effort to commemorate his virtue and great contributions to modern karate-do as a pioneer, we, his loyal students, organised the Shotokai and erected this monument at the Enkakuji. \u201cKenzen ichi\u201d (\u201cThe fist and Zen are one\u201d). | cquote}}\n\n==Publications==\n*{{cite book |title= T\u014d-te Ry\u016bky\u016b Kenp\u014d (\u5510\u624b : \u7409\u7403\u62f3\u6cd5) |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |year=1922 |url= http://kindai.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/971654?}}\n*{{cite book |title= Karate Jutsu (\u5510\u624b\u8853) |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |year= 1925 |url= http://www.hawaii.edu/asiaref/okinawa/digital_archives/pdfs/funakoshi-retan1926.pdf |access-date= 2014-11-29 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150924025457/http://www.hawaii.edu/asiaref/okinawa/digital_archives/pdfs/funakoshi-retan1926.pdf |archive-date= 2015-09-24 |url-status= dead }}\n*{{cite book |title= Karate-Do Kyohan (\u7a7a\u624b\u9053\u6559\u7bc4 ) |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |year= 1935 |url= http://www.hawaii.edu/asiaref/okinawa/digital_archives/pdfs/funakoshi-kyohon1935.pdf |access-date= 2014-03-04 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141129114056/http://www.hawaii.edu/asiaref/okinawa/digital_archives/pdfs/funakoshi-kyohon1935.pdf |archive-date= 2014-11-29 |url-status= dead }}\n*{{cite book |title= Karate-Do Kyohan: The Master Text |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |translator=Tsutomu Ohshima |translator-link=Tsutomu Ohshima |year=1973 |publisher=Kodansha International |location=Tokyo |isbn=978-0-87011-190-7 }}\n*{{cite book |title=The Twenty Guiding Principles of Karate: The Spiritual Legacy of the Master |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |year=1975 |translator=John Teramoto |publisher=Kodansha International |location=Tokyo |isbn=978-4-7700-2796-2 }}\n*{{cite book |title=Karate-Do: My Way of Life |last=Funakoshi |first=Gichin |year=1981 |origyear=1975 |publisher=Kodansha International |location=Tokyo |isbn=978-0-87011-463-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/karatedomywayofl00funa }}\n*{{cite book |title= Karate-Do Nyumon: The Master Introductory Text |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |translator=John Teramoto |year=1994 |origyear=1988 |publisher=Kodansha International |location=Tokyo |isbn=978-4-7700-1891-5 }}\n*{{cite book |title=Karate Jutsu: The Original Teachings of Master Funakoshi |translator=Tsutomu Ohshima |translator-link=Tsutomu Ohshima |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |year=2001 |publisher=Kodansha International |location=Tokyo |isbn=978-4-7700-2681-1 }}\n*{{cite book |title=The Essence of Karate |translator=Richard Berger |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |year=2010 |publisher=Kodansha International |location=Tokyo |isbn=978-4-7700-3118-1 }}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Shotokan organizations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n <!-- Goes above DEFAULTSORT/Categories -->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Karate}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Funakoshi, Gichin}}\n[[Category:1868 births]]\n[[Category:1957 deaths]]\n[[Category:Martial arts school founders]]\n[[Category:Martial arts writers]]\n[[Category:Okinawan male karateka]]\n[[Category:Shotokan practitioners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Karateka}}\n{{Okinawan name|Funakoshi}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name = Gichin Funakoshi\n| native_name = {{nihongo2|\u8239\u8d8a \u7fa9\u73cd}} \n| native_name_lang = jp\n| residence = \n| other_names = ''Sh\u014dt\u014d'' ([[wikt:\u677e|\u677e]][[wikt:\u6fe4|\u6fe4]])\n| image = [[File:Master Gichin Funakoshi.jpg|thumb|Master Gichin Funakoshi]]\n| image_size = \n| caption = Gichin Funakoshi, ''c.'' 1950\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1868|11|10|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Shuri, Okinawa|Shuri]], [[Ryukyu Kingdom]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1957|04|26|1868|11|10|mf=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Tokyo, Japan]]\n| death_cause = \n| martial_art = [[Sh\u014drei-ry\u016b]], [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b]], and [[Sh\u014dt\u014dkan|Shotokan]] [[Karate]]\n| teacher = [[Ank\u014d Asato]], [[Ank\u014d Itosu]], [[Matsumura S\u014dkon]]\n| rank = 5th dan, 10th ''[[Dan rank|dan]]'' (postmortem)\n| students = [[Hironori \u014ctsuka]], [[Gig\u014d Funakoshi]] (his son), [[Isao Obata]], [[:de:Gima Makoto|Makoto Gima]] [[Shigeru Egami]], [[Teruyuki Okazaki]], [[Tetsuhiko Asai]], [[Masatoshi Nakayama]], [[Yasuhiro Konishi]], [[Hidetaka Nishiyama]], [[Tsutomu Ohshima]], [[Taiji Kase]], [[Mitsusuke Harada]], [[Hirokazu Kanazawa]], [[Won Kuk Lee]], [[Masutatsu Oyama]], [[Tetsuji Murakami]], [[Yutaka Yaguchi]], [[Won Kuk Lee]], [[Song Moo Kwan|Byung Jik Ro]], [[Choi Hong Hi]]\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Gichin Funakoshi'''|\u8239\u8d8a \u7fa9\u73cd|Funakoshi Gichin|November 10, 1868&nbsp;\u2013 April 26, 1957}} is the founder of [[Shotokan]] [[Karate|Karate-Do]], perhaps the most widely known style of karate, and is known as a \"father of modern karate\".<ref>{{cite book | title=Karate Jutsu: The Original Teachings of Master Funakoshi | publisher=Kodansha International Ltd | author=Funakoshi, Gichin | translator=John Teramoto | year=2001 |isbn= 4-7700-2681-1}}</ref> Following the teachings of [[Anko Itosu]] and [[Anko Asato]],<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\">Funakoshi, Gichin (1981). ''Karate-Do: My Way of Life'', Kodansha International Ltd. {{ISBN|0-87011-463-8}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gichinfunakoshi.com/gichin.htm |title=GichinFunakoshi.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005220243/http://www.gichinfunakoshi.com/gichin.htm |archivedate=2012-10-05 }}</ref> he was one of the Okinawan [[karate]] [[Grandmaster (martial arts)|masters]] who introduced karate to the Japanese mainland in 1922. He taught karate at various Japanese universities and became honorary head of the [[Japan Karate Association]] upon its establishment in 1949.\n\n==Early life==\nGichin Funakoshi was born on November 10, 1868,<ref>{{Cite book|author=Gichin Funakoshi |title=Karate-d\u014d, My Way of Life }}</ref> the year of the [[Meiji Restoration]], in [[Shuri, Okinawa]], to a low-rank Ry\u016bky\u016ban [[Pechin]]. He originally had the family name Tominakoshi.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.24fightingchickens.com/2006/01/29/funakoshi-man-vs-myth/ | title = Deconstructing Funakoshi}}</ref> Funakoshi was born [[premature birth|prematurely]]. His father's name was Gisu.<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\"/> After entering primary school he became close friends with the son of [[Ank\u014d Asato]], a karate and [[Jigen-ry\u016b]] master who would soon become his first karate teacher.<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\"/> \n\u2212\t\nFunakoshi's family was stiffly opposed to the Meiji government's abolition of the Japanese [[Chonmage|topknot]], and this meant that he would be ineligible to pursue his goal of attending medical school (where topknots were banned), despite having passed the entrance examination.<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\"/> Being trained in both classical Chinese and Japanese philosophies and teachings, Funakoshi became an assistant teacher in Okinawa. During this time, his relations with the Asato family grew and he began nightly travels to the Asato family residence to receive karate instruction from Ank\u014d Asato.<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\"/>\n\n==Shotokan Karate==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=November 2017}}\nFunakoshi had trained in both of the popular styles of Okinawan [[karate]] of the time: [[Sh\u014drei-ry\u016b]] and [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b]]. Shotokan is named after Funakoshi's pen name, ''Sh\u014dt\u014d'' ([[wikt:\u677e|\u677e]][[wikt:\u6fe4|\u6fe4]]), which means \"waving pines\".  ''Kan'' means training hall or house, thus ''Sh\u014dt\u014dkan'' (\u677e\u6fe4\u9928) referred to the \"house of Sh\u014dt\u014d\". This name was coined by Funakoshi's students when they posted a sign above the entrance of the hall at which Funakoshi taught. In addition to being a karate master, Funakoshi was an avid [[poet]] and [[philosopher]] who would reportedly go for long walks in the forest where he would [[meditation|meditate]] and write his poetry.<ref name=\"threemasters\">John Stevens (1995). \"Three Budo Masters: Kano, Funakoshi, Ueshiba\". Kodansha International {{ISBN|4-7700-1852-5}}</ref>\n\nBy the late 1910s, Funakoshi had many students, of which a few were deemed capable of passing on their master's teachings. Continuing his effort to garner widespread interest in Okinawan karate, Funakoshi ventured to mainland Japan in 1917, and again in 1922.<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\" />\n\nIn 1930, Funakoshi established an association named Dai-Nihon Karate-do Kenkyukai to promote communication and information exchange among people who study karate-d\u014d. In 1936, Dai-Nippon Karate-do Kenkyukai changed its name to Dai-Nippon Karate-do Shoto-kai.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shotokai.jp/english/about/history.html |title=The Official Homepage of Nihon Karate-do Shotokai |access-date=2010-08-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100227032101/http://www.shotokai.jp/english/about/history.html |archive-date=2010-02-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The association is known today as [[Shotokai]], and is the official keeper of Funakoshi's karate heritage.\n\nIn 1936, Funakoshi built the first Sh\u014dt\u014dkan ''[[dojo]]'' (training hall) in Tokyo. While on the Japanese mainland, he changed the [[kanji|written characters]]  of karate to mean \"empty hand\" (\u7a7a\u624b) instead of \"China hand\" (\u5510\u624b) (literally [[Tang dynasty]]) to downplay its connection to [[Chinese boxing]]. Karate had borrowed many aspects from Chinese boxing.  Funakoshi also argued in his autobiography that a philosophical evaluation of the use of \"empty\" seemed to fit as it implied a way which was not tethered to any other physical object.\n\nFunakoshi's re-interpretation of the [[kanji|character]] ''kara'' in karate to mean \"empty\" ([[wikt:\u7a7a|\u7a7a]]) rather than \"Chinese\" ([[wikt:\u5510|\u5510]])  caused some tension with traditionalists back in Okinawa, prompting Funakoshi to remain in [[Tokyo]] indefinitely.{{citation needed|date=May 2010}} In 1949 Funakoshi's students created the [[Japan Karate Association]] (JKA), with Funakoshi as the honorary head of the organization. However, in practise this organization was led by [[Masatoshi Nakayama]]. The JKA began formalizing Funakoshi's teachings. Funakoshi was not supportive of all of the changes that the JKA eventually made to his karate style. He resigned from the JKA in 1956 in order to reduce friction between the JKA and Shotokai.\n\n==Illness and death==\nFunakoshi developed [[osteoarthritis]] in 1948, and died of [[colorectal cancer]] in 1957.\n\n==Legacy==\nFunakoshi published several books on karate including his autobiography, ''Karate-Do: My Way of Life''. His legacy, however, rests in a document containing his philosophies of karate training now referred to as the ''[[niju kun]]'', or \"twenty principles\".  These rules are the premise of training for all Shotokan practitioners and are published in a work titled ''The Twenty Guiding Principles of Karate''.<ref>{{cite book | title=The Twenty Guiding Principles of Karate: The Spiritual Legacy of the Master  | publisher=Kodansha International Ltd | author=Funakoshi, Gichin | translator=John Teramoto| year=1975 |isbn=4-7700-2796-6}}</ref> Within this book, Funakoshi lays out 20 rules by which students of karate are urged to abide in an effort to \"become better human beings\".<ref name=\"funakoshi_autobiography\" /> Funakoshi's Karate-Do Kyohan \"The Master Text\" remains his most detailed publication, containing sections on history, basics, [[kata]], and [[kumite]]. The famous Shotokan Tiger by Hoan<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.funakoshibooks.com/?p=8 | title = Kosugi Hoan Shotokan Tiger}}</ref> adorns the hardback cover.\n\n==Memorial==\n[[File:funakoshi memorial.jpg|thumb|right|Memorial for Funakoshi at Engaku-ji temple in Kamakura, south of Tokyo]]\n\nA memorial to Gichin Funakoshi was erected by the Shotokai at [[Engaku-ji]], a temple in [[Kamakura, Kanagawa|Kamakura]], on December 1, 1968. Designed by Kenji Ogata the monument features calligraphy by Funakoshi and [[S\u014dgen Asahina]] (1891\u20131979), chief priest of the temple which reads ''Karate ni sente nashi'' (There is no first attack in karate), the second of Funakoshi\u2019s Twenty Precepts.  To the right of Funakoshi\u2019s precept is a copy of the poem he wrote on his way to Japan in 1922.\n\nA second stone features an inscription by Nobuhide Ohama and reads:<ref>{{cite book | last = Cook | first = Harry | title = Shotokan Karate: A Precise History | publisher = Cook | year = 2001 | location = England }}</ref>\n\n{{cquote | Funakoshi Gichin Sensei, of karate-do, was born on November 10, 1868 in Shuri Okinawa. From about eleven years old he began to study to-te jutsu under [[Azato Anko]] and [[Itosu Anko]]. He practiced diligently and in 1912 became the president of the Okinawan Shobukai. In May 1922, he relocated to Tokyo and became a professional teacher of karate-do. He devoted his entire life to the development of karate-do. He lived out his eighty-eight years of life and left this world on April 26, 1957. Reinterpreting to-te jutsu, the Sensei promulgated karate-do while not losing its original philosophy. Like bugei (classical martial arts), so too is the pinnacle of karate \u201cmu\u201d (enlightenment): to purify and make one empty through the transformation from \u201cjutsu\u201d to \u201cdo\u201d. Through his famous words \"\u7a7a\u624b\u306b\u5148\u624b\u306a\u3057\" (karate ni sente nashi) meaning ''There is no first attack in Karate'' and \u7a7a\u624b\u306f\u541b\u5b50\u306e\u6b66\u82b8 (karate wa kunshi no bugei) meaning ''Karate is the martial art of intelligent people'', Sensei helped us to better understand the term \u201cjutsu.\u201d In an effort to commemorate his virtue and great contributions to modern karate-do as a pioneer, we, his loyal students, organised the Shotokai and erected this monument at the Enkakuji. \u201cKenzen ichi\u201d (\u201cThe fist and Zen are one\u201d). | cquote}}\n\n==Publications==\n*{{cite book |title= T\u014d-te Ry\u016bky\u016b Kenp\u014d (\u5510\u624b : \u7409\u7403\u62f3\u6cd5) |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |year=1922 |url= http://kindai.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/971654?}}\n*{{cite book |title= Karate Jutsu (\u5510\u624b\u8853) |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |year= 1925 |url= http://www.hawaii.edu/asiaref/okinawa/digital_archives/pdfs/funakoshi-retan1926.pdf |access-date= 2014-11-29 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150924025457/http://www.hawaii.edu/asiaref/okinawa/digital_archives/pdfs/funakoshi-retan1926.pdf |archive-date= 2015-09-24 |url-status= dead }}\n*{{cite book |title= Karate-Do Kyohan (\u7a7a\u624b\u9053\u6559\u7bc4 ) |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |year= 1935 |url= http://www.hawaii.edu/asiaref/okinawa/digital_archives/pdfs/funakoshi-kyohon1935.pdf |access-date= 2014-03-04 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141129114056/http://www.hawaii.edu/asiaref/okinawa/digital_archives/pdfs/funakoshi-kyohon1935.pdf |archive-date= 2014-11-29 |url-status= dead }}\n*{{cite book |title= Karate-Do Kyohan: The Master Text |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |translator=Tsutomu Ohshima |translator-link=Tsutomu Ohshima |year=1973 |publisher=Kodansha International |location=Tokyo |isbn=978-0-87011-190-7 }}\n*{{cite book |title=The Twenty Guiding Principles of Karate: The Spiritual Legacy of the Master |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |year=1975 |translator=John Teramoto |publisher=Kodansha International |location=Tokyo |isbn=978-4-7700-2796-2 }}\n*{{cite book |title=Karate-Do: My Way of Life |last=Funakoshi |first=Gichin |year=1981 |origyear=1975 |publisher=Kodansha International |location=Tokyo |isbn=978-0-87011-463-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/karatedomywayofl00funa }}\n*{{cite book |title= Karate-Do Nyumon: The Master Introductory Text |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |translator=John Teramoto |year=1994 |origyear=1988 |publisher=Kodansha International |location=Tokyo |isbn=978-4-7700-1891-5 }}\n*{{cite book |title=Karate Jutsu: The Original Teachings of Master Funakoshi |translator=Tsutomu Ohshima |translator-link=Tsutomu Ohshima |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |year=2001 |publisher=Kodansha International |location=Tokyo |isbn=978-4-7700-2681-1 }}\n*{{cite book |title=The Essence of Karate |translator=Richard Berger |last= Funakoshi |first= Gichin |year=2010 |publisher=Kodansha International |location=Tokyo |isbn=978-4-7700-3118-1 }}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Shotokan organizations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n <!-- Goes above DEFAULTSORT/Categories -->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Karate}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Funakoshi, Gichin}}\n[[Category:1868 births]]\n[[Category:1957 deaths]]\n[[Category:Martial arts school founders]]\n[[Category:Martial arts writers]]\n[[Category:Okinawan male karateka]]\n[[Category:Shotokan practitioners]]\n", "name_user": "JinKD1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gichin_Funakoshi"}
{"title_page": "List of shipwrecks in August 1844", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe '''list of shipwrecks in August 1844''' includes [[ship]]s sunk, foundered, wrecked, grounded, or otherwise lost during August [[1844]].\n{{dynamic list}}\n{{Calendar ToC}}\n==1 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=1 August 1844 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Convoy'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1837}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on \"Tuconia Island\".<ref name=A200145>{{Cite news |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/37155826 |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=The Australian |location=Sydney |date=20 January 1845 |page=2 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Isidore'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1837}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on Trundy's Reef, off [[Cape Elizabeth, Maine]]. She was on a voyage from [[Matanzas]], [[Captaincy General of Cuba|Cuba]] to [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]].<ref name=Times020944>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=2 September 1844 |page_number=7 |issue=18704 |column=B }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Laurel'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[fishing smack]] was wrecked on the Couch\u00e8e Rocks, off the coast of [[Jersey]], [[Channel Islands]] with the loss of fourteen of her twenty crew.<ref name=Times080844a>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=8 August 1844 |page_number=8 |issue=18683 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Levenlass'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Garrock Point]], [[Renfrewshire]]. She was on a voyage from [[Glasgow]], Renfrewshire to [[Montreal]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]]. She was later refloated and taken in to [[Greenock]], Renfrewshire.<ref name=MC060844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Wilberforce'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Middenplat, in the [[North Sea]] off the Dutch coast. She was on a voyage from [[Dundee]], [[Forfarshire]] to [[Exeter]], [[Devon]]. She was refloated the next day.<ref name=CM120844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==2 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=2 August 1844 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Anne'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered n the [[Bristol Channel]] off [[The Mumbles]], [[Glamorgan]].<ref name=BC/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Friends'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[sloop]] foundered in the Bristol Channel off [[Lundy Island]], [[Devon]] with the loss of all on board.<ref name=TEFP150844>{{Cite news |title=North Devon |newspaper=Trewman's Exeter Flying Post |location=Exeter |date=15 August 1844 |issue=4110 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Integrity'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] foundered off the coast of [[Cornwall]] with the loss of all six crew. The wreck subsequently came ashore at [[Northcott, Cornwall|Northcott]].<ref name=S060844/><ref name=BM100844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Julia'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[sloop]] was driven ashore at [[Worms Head]], Glamorgan with the loss of a crew member. She was on a voyage from [[Bridgwater]], [[Somerset]] to [[Dublin]].<ref name=BC/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Maria'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was wrecked off [[Tenby]], [[Pembrokeshire]] with the loss of all but three of her crew.<ref name=MC130844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Maria'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship departed from [[St. Jago de Cuba]], [[Captaincy General of Cuba|Cuba]] for [[Llanelly]], Glamorgan. No further trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=MC271244>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=The Morning Chronicle |location=London |date=27 December 1844 |issue=23453 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was wrecked near [[Rhosilli]], Glamorgan with the loss of a passenger.<ref name=BC/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rose'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship departed from [[Penzance]], [[Cornwall]] for a Welsh port. No further trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=S140844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Thetis'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The schooner foundered in [[Oxwich Bay]] Her four crew were rescued by ''Affo'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=BC/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Triton'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Port Eynon Point]], Glamorgan with the loss of five of her six crew. She was on a voyage from [[Par, Cornwall]] to [[Swansea]], Glamorgan.<ref name=BC/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Valiant'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the West Barrows, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Essex]]. She was on a voyage from [[Limerick]] to [[London]]. She was refloated and taken in to the [[River Colne, Essex|River Colne]].<ref name=S050844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Whim'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was wrecked in [[Kynance Cove]], [[Cornwall]] with the loss of all five of her crew.<ref name=Times130844>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Fatal Shipwreck |date=13 August 1844 |page_number=5 |issue=18687 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=S060844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=3 August 1844 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Active'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and severely damaged at [[Porthcawl]], [[Glamorgan]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Newport, Monmouthshire]] to [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]].<ref name=MC060844/><ref name=CM120844/> She was refloated on 6 August.<ref name=Times080844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Alliance'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and scuttled at [[Caldy Island]], [[Pembrokeshire]]. She had been refloated by 6 August.<ref name=MC090844/><ref name=MP100844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ann'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship sank at [[The Mumbles]], Glamorgan. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Cardiff]], Glamorgan to [[London]].<ref name=MP070844/> She was refloated on 18 August.<ref name=Times210844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Arama'' \n|flag={{flag|Netherlands}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and wrecked between \"Zeeburg\" and [[Brielle]], [[South Holland]]. She was on a voyage from [[Ventspils]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]] to [[Rotterdam]], South Holland.<ref name=MC090844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Breeze'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in [[Carmarthen Bay]].<ref name=MC090844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Briton'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship|steam]] [[tugboat|tug]] sank at [[Bristol]], [[Gloucestershire]].<ref name=LWLN110844>{{Cite news |title=The Late Hurricane at Sea |newspaper=Lloyd's Weekly London Newspaper |location=London |date=11 August 1844 |issue=90 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Brothers'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Wicklow]].<ref name=Times080844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Catherine and Mary'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was run down and sunk in the [[English Channel]] off [[Dungeness (headland)|Dungeness]], [[Kent]] with the loss of two of her four crew. Survivors were rescued by the [[coastal trading vessel|coaster]] ''Despatch'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Catherine and Mary'' was on a voyage from [[Porthmadog|Port Madoc]], [[Caernarfonshire]] to [[Ipswich]], [[Suffolk]].<ref name=Times080844>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Disasters at Sea |date=8 August 1844 |page_number=7 |issue=18683 |column=D }}</ref><ref name=MP070844>{{Cite news |title=Ship News |newspaper=The Morning Post |location=London |date=7 August 1844 |issue=22954 |page=8 }}</ref><ref name=HP090844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Commerce'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was lost near [[St. David's Head]], Pembrokeshire. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=MC090844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Estafette'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Havre de Gr\u00e2ce]], [[Seine-Inf\u00e9rieure]].<ref name=MP070844a>{{Cite news |title=The Late Hurricane |newspaper=The Morning Post |location=London |date=7 August 1844 |issue=22953 |page=8 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Friends'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the Cefn Sands, in Carmarthen Bay with the loss of all on board.<ref name=MC060844>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=The Morning Chronicle |location=London |date=6 August 1844 |issue=23329 }}</ref><ref name=MP060844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Friends'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and scuttled at Caldy Island She had been refloated by 6 August.<ref name=MP100844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Four Brothers'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[fishing smack]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Tenby]], [[Pembrokeshire]] with the loss of two of her crew.<ref name=MP060844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Harmony'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and scuttled at Caldy Islands. She had been refloated by 6 August.<ref name=MC090844/><ref name=MP100844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Hope'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore in [[Saint Tudwal's Islands]], [[Caernarfonshire]].<ref name=Times080844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jane'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[fishing smack]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Pendine]], [[Carmarthenshire]].<ref name=MP060844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jane and Elizabeth'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore in Saint Tudwal's Islands.<ref name=Times080844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Margaret'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore and wrecked in [[Broughton Bay]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Rotterdam]], [[South Holland]], Netherland to [[Bristol]], [[Gloucestershire]].<ref name=BC>{{cite web |url=http://www.swanseadocks.co.uk/Gower%20wrecks%20Rons%20write-up%20site.pdf |title=A Chronology of Bristol Channel Shipwrecks |first=Ron |last=Tovey |publisher=Swansea Docks |accessdate=17 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222065415/http://www.swanseadocks.co.uk/Gower%20wrecks%20Rons%20write-up%20site.pdf |archivedate=22 December 2014 }}</ref><ref name=S060844/> She was refloated on 7 September and taken in to [[Whiteford Sands|Whiteford]], Glamorgan in a severely damaged condition.<ref name=CM160944>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=16 September 1844 |issue=19398 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Medina'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] was driven ashore and wrecked on the Cefn Sands with the loss of all hands.<ref name=S060844/><ref name=BM100844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pilot'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and wrecked near [[Pwllheli]], [[Caernarfonshire]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Aberystwyth]], [[Cardiganshire]].<ref name=Times210844/><ref name=MC090844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pheasant'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at The Mumbles. She was refloated on 17 August.<ref name=Times210844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Prince of Wales'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[collier (ship type)|collier]] was wrecked on the Mouse Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Essex]]. Her crew were rescued by ''Hope'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=IJ100844>{{Cite news |title=Colchester |newspaper=The Ipswich Journal |location=Ipswich |date=10 August 1844 |issue=5495 }}</ref><ref name=NC160844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Priscilla'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore in Saint Tudwal's Islands.<ref name=Times080844a/> She was on a voyage from [[Pwllheli]], Caernarfonshire to [[Swansea]], Glamorgan.<ref name=MC080844>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=The Morning Chronicle |location=London |date=8 August 1844 |issue=23331 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Richard'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was driven ashore and wrecked at Tenby with the loss of four of her seven crew. She was on a voyage from [[Cardiff]], Glamorgan to [[London]].<ref name=S050844/><ref name=MP060844>{{Cite news |title=The Late Hurricane |newspaper=The Morning Post |location=London |date=6 August 1844 |issue=22952 }}</ref><ref name=BM100844>{{Cite news |title=The Late Gales |newspaper=The Bristol Mercury |location=Bristol |date=10 August 1844 |issue=2838 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rose'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[yacht]] was driven ashore and wrecked at Pendine. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=MP060844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Speculator'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Pembrey]], [[Carmarthenshire]].<ref name=MP070844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Superb'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Barnstaple]], [[Devon]]. She was on a voyage from [[Gloucester]] to Barnstaple.<ref name=MP070844/> She was refloated on 13 August.<ref name=S160844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Terrier'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and scuttled at Caldy Island. She had been refloated by 6 August.<ref name=MC090844>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=The Morning Chronicle |location=London |date=9 August 1844 |issue=22955 }}</ref><ref name=MP100844a>{{Cite news |title=Ship News |newspaper=The Morning Post |location=London |date=10 August 1844 |issue=22956 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Thomas Gelston'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the [[Atlantic Ocean]]. She was on a voyage from [[Belfast]], [[County Antrim]] to [[Quebec City]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]].<ref name=MC130844/><ref name=CM150844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Union'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore on the Pendine Sands. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=MC090844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Unique'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[lugger]] was driven ashore and wrecked at Havre de Gr\u00e2ce.<ref name=MP070844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Vulcan'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore in Saint Tudwal's Islands.<ref name=Times080844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Wave'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at Porthcawl. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=MC060844/> She was refloated on 15 August.<ref name=GH230844>{{Cite news |title=Ship News |newspaper=The Glasgow Herald |location=Glasgow |date=23 August 1844 |issue=4337 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Xenia'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was lost off St. Davids Head. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Charleston, South Carolina]], United States to Liverpool.<ref name=MC090844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''X. L.'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was ran aground on the Newcombe Sand, in the [[English Channel]] off the coast of [[Kent]] and foundered. Her crew were rescued by ''Alert'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''X. L.'' was on a voyage from [[Hartlepool]], [[County Durham]] to [[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]].<ref name=Times080844/><ref name=S050844>{{Cite news |title=Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=5 August 1844 |issue=6255 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 August 1844 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Brama'' \n|flag={{flag|Kingdom of Hanover|civil}}\n|desc=The ship capsized off [[Brielle]], [[South Holland]], Netherlands. All five people on board were rescued by {{PS|Columbine|1826|2}} ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Brama'' was on a voyage from [[Windau]], [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]] to [[Rotterdam]], South Holland.<ref name=MP060844a>{{Cite news |title=Five Lives Saved by the Columbine Steamer |newspaper=The Morning Post |location=London |date=6 August 1844 |issue=22952 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Dart'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Tenby]], [[Pembrokeshire]]. She was on a voyage from [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]] to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]].<ref name=S060844>{{Cite news |title=Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=6 August 1844 |issue=6256 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Prince of Wales'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was wrecked on the Mouse Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Essex]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[South Shields]], [[County Durham]] to [[London]].<ref name=Times080844a/><ref name=MC080844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sarah'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship sank in the [[English Channel]] west of [[Dungeness (headland)|Dungeness]], [[Kent]].<ref name=HP090844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==5 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=5 August 1844 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Alfred'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[sailing barge]] sprang a leak and was run aground on the Maplin Sands, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Essex]]. She was on a voyage from [[Harwich]], Essex to [[London]]. She was later refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=ES090844>{{Cite news |title=Harwich |newspaper=The Essex Standard |location=London |date=9 August 1844 |issue=711 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Harebell'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[St Just in Penwith|St. Just]], [[Cornwall]]. She was on a voyage from [[Kertch]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]] to [[London]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=NC090844>{{Cite news |title=Marine Intelligece |newspaper=The Newcastle Courant etc |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=9 August 1844 |issue=8853 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sharon'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the [[Goodwin Sands]], [[Kent]]. She was on a voyage from [[Cronstadt]], Russia to [[St. Ubes]]. Portugal. She was refloated and taken in to [[Ramsgate]], Kent in a leaky condition.<ref name=CM120844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==6 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 August 1844 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Adelaide'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore near [[Nefyn]], [[Caernarfonshire]].<ref name=S140844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Behering'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked at \"Jeyerit Fatmi\", on the [[Red Sea]] coast of Africa and opposite [[Mocha, Yemen|Mocha]]. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=Times041044>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=4 October 1844 |page_number=7