from [[Odessa]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]] to London. She was refloated but consequently put in to [[Malta]] in a leaky condition, arriving on 2 September.<ref name=GH130944/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pandora'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship caught fire in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] before 21 August.<ref name=Times290844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Providence'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on \"Langlais Island\". Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Richibucto, New Brunswick]], [[British North America]] to [[Cork (city)|Cork]].<ref name=Times020944/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Spray'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and sank at Havre de Gr\u00e2ce. She was on a voyage from [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]] to Havre de Gr\u00e2ce. ''Spray'' was refloated and taken in to port but sank again due to damage sustained.<ref name=Times210844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Syrinx'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship sank off [[Boon Island]], [[Maine]], United States before 5 August. She was on a voyage from the [[River Clyde|Clyde]] to [[Boston, Massachusetts]], United States. She was refloated and taken in to [[Saco, Maine]].<ref name=GH020944>{{Cite news |title=Ship News |newspaper=Glasgow Herald |location=Glasgow |date=2 September 1844 |issue=4340 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Three Sostre'' \n|flag={{flag|Norway|1844}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the North Sea. Her crew were rescued by ''Rosa'' ([[File:POL Ko\u0142obrzeg flag.svg|22px|border]] [[Kolberg]]). ''Three Sostre'' was on a voyage from [[Greifswald]] to  [[Guernsey]], [[Channel Islands]].<ref name=Times211044>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=21 October 1844 |page_number=7 |issue=18747 |column=E }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n{{shipevents|1844}}\n{{1840s shipwrecks}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of shipwrecks by year|1844-08]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in August 1844| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe '''list of shipwrecks in August 1844''' includes [[ship]]s sunk, foundered, wrecked, grounded, or otherwise lost during August [[1844]].\n{{dynamic list}}\n{{Calendar ToC}}\n==1 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=1 August 1844 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Convoy'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1837}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on \"Tuconia Island\".<ref name=A200145>{{Cite news |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/37155826 |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=The Australian |location=Sydney |date=20 January 1845 |page=2 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Isidore'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1837}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on Trundy's Reef, off [[Cape Elizabeth, Maine]]. She was on a voyage from [[Matanzas]], [[Captaincy General of Cuba|Cuba]] to [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]].<ref name=Times020944>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=2 September 1844 |page_number=7 |issue=18704 |column=B }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Laurel'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[fishing smack]] was wrecked on the Couch\u00e8e Rocks, off the coast of [[Jersey]], [[Channel Islands]] with the loss of fourteen of her twenty crew.<ref name=Times080844a>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=8 August 1844 |page_number=8 |issue=18683 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Levenlass'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Garrock Point]], [[Renfrewshire]]. She was on a voyage from [[Glasgow]], Renfrewshire to [[Montreal]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]]. She was later refloated and taken in to [[Greenock]], Renfrewshire.<ref name=MC060844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Wilberforce'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Middenplat, in the [[North Sea]] off the Dutch coast. She was on a voyage from [[Dundee]], [[Forfarshire]] to [[Exeter]], [[Devon]]. She was refloated the next day.<ref name=CM120844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==2 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=2 August 1844 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Anne'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered n the [[Bristol Channel]] off [[The Mumbles]], [[Glamorgan]].<ref name=BC/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Friends'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[sloop]] foundered in the Bristol Channel off [[Lundy Island]], [[Devon]] with the loss of all on board.<ref name=TEFP150844>{{Cite news |title=North Devon |newspaper=Trewman's Exeter Flying Post |location=Exeter |date=15 August 1844 |issue=4110 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Integrity'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] foundered off the coast of [[Cornwall]] with the loss of all six crew. The wreck subsequently came ashore at [[Northcott, Cornwall|Northcott]].<ref name=S060844/><ref name=BM100844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Julia'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[sloop]] was driven ashore at [[Worms Head]], Glamorgan with the loss of a crew member. She was on a voyage from [[Bridgwater]], [[Somerset]] to [[Dublin]].<ref name=BC/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Maria'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was wrecked off [[Tenby]], [[Pembrokeshire]] with the loss of all but three of her crew.<ref name=MC130844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Maria'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship departed from [[St. Jago de Cuba]], [[Captaincy General of Cuba|Cuba]] for [[Llanelly]], Glamorgan. No further trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=MC271244>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=The Morning Chronicle |location=London |date=27 December 1844 |issue=23453 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was wrecked near [[Rhosilli]], Glamorgan with the loss of a passenger.<ref name=BC/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rose'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship departed from [[Penzance]], [[Cornwall]] for a Welsh port. No further trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=S140844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Thetis'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The schooner foundered in [[Oxwich Bay]] Her four crew were rescued by ''Affo'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=BC/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Triton'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Port Eynon Point]], Glamorgan with the loss of five of her six crew. She was on a voyage from [[Par, Cornwall]] to [[Swansea]], Glamorgan.<ref name=BC/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Valiant'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the West Barrows, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Essex]]. She was on a voyage from [[Limerick]] to [[London]]. She was refloated and taken in to the [[River Colne, Essex|River Colne]].<ref name=S050844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Whim'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was wrecked in [[Kynance Cove]], [[Cornwall]] with the loss of all five of her crew.<ref name=Times130844>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Fatal Shipwreck |date=13 August 1844 |page_number=5 |issue=18687 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=S060844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=3 August 1844 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Active'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and severely damaged at [[Porthcawl]], [[Glamorgan]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Newport, Monmouthshire]] to [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]].<ref name=MC060844/><ref name=CM120844/> She was refloated on 6 August.<ref name=Times080844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Alliance'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and scuttled at [[Caldy Island]], [[Pembrokeshire]]. She had been refloated by 6 August.<ref name=MC090844/><ref name=MP100844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ann'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship sank at [[The Mumbles]], Glamorgan. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Cardiff]], Glamorgan to [[London]].<ref name=MP070844/> She was refloated on 18 August.<ref name=Times210844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Arama'' \n|flag={{flag|Netherlands}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and wrecked between \"Zeeburg\" and [[Brielle]], [[South Holland]]. She was on a voyage from [[Ventspils]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]] to [[Rotterdam]], South Holland.<ref name=MC090844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Breeze'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in [[Carmarthen Bay]].<ref name=MC090844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Briton'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship|steam]] [[tugboat|tug]] sank at [[Bristol]], [[Gloucestershire]].<ref name=LWLN110844>{{Cite news |title=The Late Hurricane at Sea |newspaper=Lloyd's Weekly London Newspaper |location=London |date=11 August 1844 |issue=90 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Brothers'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Wicklow]].<ref name=Times080844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Catherine and Mary'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was run down and sunk in the [[English Channel]] off [[Dungeness (headland)|Dungeness]], [[Kent]] with the loss of two of her four crew. Survivors were rescued by the [[coastal trading vessel|coaster]] ''Despatch'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Catherine and Mary'' was on a voyage from [[Porthmadog|Port Madoc]], [[Caernarfonshire]] to [[Ipswich]], [[Suffolk]].<ref name=Times080844>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Disasters at Sea |date=8 August 1844 |page_number=7 |issue=18683 |column=D }}</ref><ref name=MP070844>{{Cite news |title=Ship News |newspaper=The Morning Post |location=London |date=7 August 1844 |issue=22954 |page=8 }}</ref><ref name=HP090844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Commerce'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was lost near [[St. David's Head]], Pembrokeshire. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=MC090844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Estafette'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Havre de Gr\u00e2ce]], [[Seine-Inf\u00e9rieure]].<ref name=MP070844a>{{Cite news |title=The Late Hurricane |newspaper=The Morning Post |location=London |date=7 August 1844 |issue=22953 |page=8 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Friends'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the Cefn Sands, in Carmarthen Bay with the loss of all on board.<ref name=MC060844>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=The Morning Chronicle |location=London |date=6 August 1844 |issue=23329 }}</ref><ref name=MP060844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Friends'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and scuttled at Caldy Island She had been refloated by 6 August.<ref name=MP100844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Four Brothers'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[fishing smack]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Tenby]], [[Pembrokeshire]] with the loss of two of her crew.<ref name=MP060844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Harmony'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and scuttled at Caldy Islands. She had been refloated by 6 August.<ref name=MC090844/><ref name=MP100844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Hope'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore in [[Saint Tudwal's Islands]], [[Caernarfonshire]].<ref name=Times080844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jane'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[fishing smack]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Pendine]], [[Carmarthenshire]].<ref name=MP060844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jane and Elizabeth'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore in Saint Tudwal's Islands.<ref name=Times080844a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Margaret'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore and wrecked in [[Broughton Bay]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Rotterdam]], [[South Holland]], Netherland to [[Bristol]], [[Gloucestershire]].<ref name=BC>{{cite web |url=http://www.swanseadocks.co.uk/Gower%20wrecks%20Rons%20write-up%20site.pdf |title=A Chronology of Bristol Channel Shipwrecks |first=Ron |last=Tovey |publisher=Swansea Docks |accessdate=17 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222065415/http://www.swanseadocks.co.uk/Gower%20wrecks%20Rons%20write-up%20site.pdf |archivedate=22 December 2014 }}</ref><ref name=S060844/> She was refloated on 7 September and taken in to [[Whiteford Sands|Whiteford]], Glamorgan in a severely damaged condition.<ref name=CM160944>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=16 September 1844 |issue=19398 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Medina'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] was driven ashore and wrecked on the Cefn Sands with the loss of all hands.<ref name=S060844/><ref name=BM100844/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pilot'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and wrecked near [[Pwllheli]], [[Caernarfonshire]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Aberystwyth]], [[Cardiganshire]]